ce:section.ce:para:
The fluorescent response of the CQDs/Ab probe for different concentrations of AFM1 (0.01–1 ng/mL) was studied under the optimized experimental conditions. As shown in Fig. 4
                        A, the fluorescent intensity of the CQDs/Ab probe decreased gradually with the increasing AFM1 concentrations. This fluorescent quenching behavior of the CQDs/Ab sensor was quite sensitive (e.g., even to 1 ng/mL) and reasonably fast. This concentration-dependent fluorescent quenching of the nanosensor was caused by the reduction in the effective excitation energy available to the CQDs/Ab probe after the binding of AFM1 with the anti-AFM1 antibody loaded CQDs. Moreover, a slight blue shift in the fluorescence emission peak was observed (towards 425 nm), which could be attributed to the auto-fluorescence properties of the AFM1 (Herzallah, 2009; Hruska et al., 2014). The analyte concentrations have been plotted against the fluorescence quenching (Fig. 4B) and a linear relationship is attained between 0.2 and 0.8 ng/mL. According to the standard formula of S/N = 3, the limit of detection (LOD) and limit of quantification (LOQ) of the prepared nano sensing platform was calculated to be 0.07 ng/mL and 0.21 ng/mL, respectively. Thus, the developed assay showed fair detection sensitivity within a detection time of 30 min which is better sensor properties compared to the previously reported optical sensors for AFM1 (Table 1
                        ). Therefore, it can be a promising solution for fast, low-cost, and sensitive mycotoxin monitoring because of the low LOD and wide dynamic range.
